Taxonomic catalogue of Heliconiinae

06 January 2025

Order: Lepidoptera Linnaeus, 1758

Family: Nymphalidae Rafinesque, 1815

Subfamily: Heliconiinae Swainson, 1822

Resources:

Tribe Acraeini

Type genus: Acraea Fabricius, 1807

Classification: The tribe Acraeini is divided into eight genera (Williams and Hennig 2023): Acraea, Actinote, Bematistes, Cethosia, Rubraea, Stephenia, Telchinia and Tildia.

References: Penz and Peggie (2003) (phylogeny); Vane-Wright and Jong (2003) (Sulawesi); Silva-Brando et al. (2008) (phylogeny); Henning and Williams (2010) (taxonomy); Timmermans et al. (2016) (phylogeny); Pierre (2020 a) (Uganda); Lang et al. (2022) (taxonomy; China); Williams and Hennig (2023) (taxonomy)

Genus Acraea

Genus: Acraea Fabricius, 1807

Type species: Acraea hortaLinnaeus, 1764; original combination: Papilio hortaLinnaeus, 1764

Synonyms:

  • Aphanopeltis Mabille, 1887. Type species: Acraea hortaLinnaeus, 1764; original combination: Papilio hortaLinnaeus, 1764. Refs.: Mabille (1886): 85
  • Phanopeltis Mabille, 1887. Type species: Acraea ranavalonaBoisduval, 1833; original combination: Acraea ranavalonaBoisduval, 1833. Refs.: Mabille (1886): 84
  • Solenites Mabille, 1887. Type species: Acraea igatiBoisduval, 1833; original combination: Acraea igatiBoisduval, 1833. Refs.: Mabille (1886): 82
  • Miyana Fruhstorfer, 1914. Type species: Acraea moluccanaFelder, 1860; original combination: Acraea moluccanaFelder, 1860. Refs.: Fruhstorfer (1912 a): 743

References: Hennig (1993 a); Williams and Hennig (2010); Pierre and Bernaud (2012) (taxonomy, phylogeny); Pierre and Bernaud (2013); Williams and Hennig (2020); Williams and Hennig (2023) (taxonomic revision)

Genus Actinote

Genus: Actinote Hbner [1819]

Type species: Actinote thalia(Linnaeus, 1758); original combination: Papilio thaliaLinnaeus, 1758

Synonyms:

  • Calornis Billberg, 1820. Type species: Actinote thalia(Linnaeus, 1758); original combination: Papilio thaliaLinnaeus, 1758. Refs.: Billberg (1820): 77
  • Abananote Potts, 1943. Type species: Actinote abana (Hewitson, 1868); original combination: Acraea abanaHewitson, 1868. Refs.: Potts (1943): 31 (as subgenus)
  • Altinote Potts, 1943. Type species: Actinote neleus(Latreille, [1813]); original combination: Heliconius neleusLatreille, [1813]. Refs.: Potts (1943): 31

References: Hbner ([1819]): 27

Genus Telchinia

Genus: Telchinia Hbner [1819]

Type species: Telchinia serena (Fabricius, 1775); original combination: Papillio serena Fabricius, 1775

Synonyms:

  • Hyalites Doubleday [1848]. Type species: Telchinia encedon (Linnaeus, 1758); original combination: Papilio lyciaFabricius, 1758. Refs.: Doubleday ([1848]): 140
  • Gnesia Doubleday [1848]. Type species: Telchinia circeis(Drury, 1782); original combination: Papilio circeisDrury, 1782. Refs.: Doubleday ([1848]): 141

  • Planema Doubleday [1848]. Type species: Telchinia lycoa(Godart, 1819); original combination: Acraea lycoaGodart, 1819. Refs.: Doubleday ([1848]): 140

Tribe Argynnini

Type genus: Argynnis [Fabricius], 1807

Classification: The tribe Argynnini is divided into four subtribes and eight genera (Simonsen 2006 a; Simonsen et al. 2006):

  • Subtribe Argynnina: Argynnis, Brenthis, Issoria

  • Subtribe Boloriina: Boloria (monobasic)

  • Subtribe Euptoietina: Euptoieta (monobasic)

  • Subtribe Yrameina: Yramea (monobasic)

  • Genus Pardopsis (no subtribe assigned).

References: Warren (1944) (taxonomy); dos Passos and Grey (1945 a) (taxonomy); Warren et al. (1946) (taxonomy); Warren (1955) (taxonomy); Lamas (2004) (Neotropics); Penz and Peggie (2003) (phylogeny); Simonsen (2006 a) (taxonomy, phylogeny); Simonsen et al. (2006) (phylogeny)

Genus Brenthis

Genus: Brenthis Hbner [1819]

Type species: Brenthis hecate([Denis & Schiffermller], 1775); original combination: Papilio hecate [Denis & Schiffermller], 1775

  • Neobrenthis Koak, 1980. Type species: Brenthis hecate([Denis & Schiffermller], 1775); original combination: Papilio hecate [Denis & Schiffermller], 1775. Refs.: Koak (1980): 30

Rainier, Pierce County]. Types: Syntype in NMNH and LACM; figured by W. Holland (1931), Butterfly Book (rev. ed.): pl. 60, figs. 9 D, 10 V. Refs.: Barnes & McDunnough, 1913, Contr. Nat. Hist. Lepid. N. Am. 2(3): 96-97, pl. 2, figs. 1 D, 2 D, 3 V, 4 V; C. Guppy and Kondla (2002), J. Lepid. Soc. 56(3): 181, suggested that this name be emended to ranieri since Mt. Ranier was misspelled in the text in the original description. The name as given in the description heading was derived from the correct spelling of the name of the mountain, and needs no emendation (Code Article 32.5.1).

Tribe Heliconiini

Type genus: Heliconius Kluk, 1780

Classification: The tribe Heliconiini is divided into eight genera based on morphological characters (Michener 1942 a): Agraulis (8 species), Dione (3 species), Dryadula (1 species), Dryas (4 species), Eueides (12 species), Heliconius (47 species), Philaethria (10 species) and Podotricha (2 species).

Characteristics: Larvae are spiny and feed on Passiflora (Passifloraceae).

Phylogenetic relationships: Extensive historical and on-going gene flow in this group makes phylogenetic inference challenging. Molecular phylogenies support the eight genera as monophyletic clades, but the relationships between many genera require further investigation.

Distribution: Neotropics; see occurrence maps by Neil Rosser

References: Michener (1942 a) (keys); Emsley (1963); Emsley (1965); Brown Jr. (1976); Brown (1981) (review); Brown and Fernndez Yepez (1984) (Venezuela); Brown Jr. et al. (1992) (chromosomes); Penz and Peggie (2003) (phylogeny); Kozak et al. (2015) (molecular phylogeny); Kozak et al. (2021) (genome phylogeny); Cicconardi et al. (2023) (genome phylogeny)

Genus Heliconius

Genus: Heliconius Kluk, 1780

Type species: Heliconius charithonia (Linnaeus, 1767); original combination: Papilio charithonia Linnaeus, 1767

Synonyms:

  • Heliconius Latreille [1804]. Type species: Heliconius charithonia (Linnaeus, 1767); original combination: Papilio charithonia Linnaeus, 1767. Refs.: Latreille (1804): 185
  • Migonitis Hbner, 1816. Type species: Heliconius erato (Linnaeus, 1758); original combination: Papilio erato (Linnaeus, 1764). Refs.: Hbner (1816): 12
  • Sunias Hbner, 1816. Type species: Heliconius melpomene (Linnaeus, 1758); original combination: Papilio melpomene Linnaeus, 1758. Refs.: Hbner (1816): 12
  • Ajantis Hbner, 1816. Type species: Heliconius sapho (Linnaeus, 1782); original combination: Papilio sapho Linnaeus, 1782. Refs.: Hbner (1816): 13
  • Apostraphia Hbner, 1816. Type species: Heliconius charithonia (Linnaeus, 1767); original combination: Papilio charithonia Linnaeus, 1767. Refs.: Hbner (1816): 13
  • Sicyonia Hbner, 1816. Type species: Heliconius sara (Fabricius, 1793); original combination: Papilio rheaCramer, 1775. Refs.: Hbner (1816): 13
  • Heliconia Latreille, 1818. Type species: Heliconius charithonia (Linnaeus, 1767); original combination: Papilio charithonia Linnaeus, 1767. Refs.: NA
  • Laparus Billberg, 1820. Type species: Heliconius doris (Linnaeus, 1771); original combination: Papilio doris (Linnaeus, 1771). Refs.: Billberg (1820): 77
  • Crenis Hbner, 1821. Type species: Heliconius doris doris (Linnaeus, 1771); original combination: Crenis brylleHbner (1821). Refs.: NA
  • Phlogris Hbner [1825]. Type species: Heliconius melpomene (Linnaeus, 1758); original combination: Papilio melpomene Linnaeus, 1758. Refs.: NA
  • Sicyonia Hbner [1826] Refs.: An unjustified emendation of Sicyonia Hbner, 1816
  • Podalirius Gistel, 1848. Type species: Heliconius charithonia (Linnaeus, 1767); original combination: Papilio charithonia Linnaeus, 1767. Refs.: Gistel (1848): ix
  • Blanchardia Buchecker [1880]. Type species: Heliconius hecuba (Hewitson, [1858]); original combination: Blanchardia dismorphia Buchecker [1880]. Refs.: NA

Phylogenetic relationships: Molecular phylogenetic studies using a small number of loci (Brower 1994; Brower and Egan 1997; Beltrn et al. 2002; Beltrn et al. 2007; Kozak et al. 2015) supported at least six clades within Heliconius: Aoede, Doris, Wallacei, Melpomene (including the silvaniforms), Erato and Sara. The relationships among these groups and among species within each group remain uncertain.

Distribution: Widespread across the Neotropics

References: Kluk (1802): 82; Emsley (1965); ICZN (2014): 204

Genus Philaethria

Genus: Philaethria Billberg, 1820

Type species: Philaethria dido (Linnaeus, 1763); original combination: Papilio dido Linnaeus, 1763

Synonyms:

  • Metamandana Stichel [1908]. Type species: Philaethria dido (Linnaeus, 1763); original combination: Papilio dido Linnaeus, 1763. Refs.: Stichel (1908): 6

Classification: Species of Philaethria have distinctive green and black wing patterns, similar to Siproeta stelenes (malachite; Nymphalidae: Nymphalinae: Victorinini) that is also found throughout the Neotropics, but they have distinct wing shapes.

Phylogenetic relationships: Phylogenetic relationships among the species remain to be investigated.

Distribution: Widespread across the Neotropics

References: Billberg (1820): 77; Michener (1942 a) (key to genus); Constantino and Salazar (2010) (key to species)

10 species:

  • andrei Brvignon, 2002

    • ssp. andrei Brvignon, 2002. Type loc.: Carapa, Macouria, French Guyana (LCB). Distr.: Lower Amazon basin in northern South America from Venezuela (El Manteco, Bolivar) to French Guiana (Carapa, Macouria) and northern Brazil (Maraj). Altitude 100200m. Rainforest habitats. Host plants: Passiflora laurifolia. Refs.: Brevignon (2002), Constantino and Salazar (2010) (to subspecies). Ety.: Andr Brvignon

    • ssp. orinocensis Constantino & Salazar, 2010. Type loc.: Delta Amacuro, Venezuela (MIZA; paratypes: JCSC). Distr.: Open grasslands in the Orinoco river basin in Venezuela up to 100m above sea level and in the state of Bolivar (rio Caura). Refs.: Constantino and Salazar (2010): 16. Ety.: Orinoco River

  • browni Constantino & Salazar, 2010. Type loc.: Barinitas, Barinas, Venezuela (MIZA; paratypes: CFC). Distr.: East slope of the Cordillera de Merida in Barinas, Venezuela. 600-1200m above sea level. Premontane forest habitats. Refs.: Constantino and Salazar (2010): 23. Ety.: Keith S. Brown
